	  When a selection is made that	is not a builtin, the host
	  interface program, as	specified in the environment variables
	  discussed above, is invoked.	The first argument is the
	  action command name.	The second argument is the message
	  number of the	selected message relative to the beginning of
	  the mail file.  Any third argument is	the string from	a
	  dynamic menu as designated by	the $$$$aaaauuuuttttoooo builtin above.  The
	  forth	argument is the	absolute message number	of the message
	  when the mail	file was last synchronized with	the terminal.
	  As messages are deleted, this	value stays the	same.  How-
	  ever,	the second argument will decrement by one for each
	  message that occurs before it	in the mail file which has
	  been deleted.	 This value is used to implement the undelete
	  function.

	  The menu item	and the	associated host	interface must,	of
	  course, be coordinated on what each command expects and
	  gets.	 As an example,	consider the following example of a
	  simple menu which allows mail	to be "saved" via strings
	  entered in a dynamic menu.


	       0:Save Mail:n,n,y,n,n,n:$auto:save

	  We might write the following shell script to provide the
